    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>Montreal</placeName>
                <date>22d Novr 5619</date>
            </p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Rev. Isaac Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Dear Sir</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">You could not<lb/> have received any request to<lb/> discontinue
                sending the Occident<lb/> to <persName>Mr Brahadi</persName> who had refused<lb/> it
                at the Post Office—and as he<lb/> says directed the clerk to take the<lb/> usual
                course of informing the<lb/> Editor per printed slip of the same.<lb/> I have
                endeavored to persuade<lb/> him to continue it—but the<lb/> only reply I got was he
                would<lb/> also discontinue the Jewish messenger<lb/> which it seems was sent
                him<lb/> without his request. He is<lb/> a London Chronicle man. Don't<lb/> be
                offended however. The Israelite<lb/> only circulates one copy here</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>the one received by your humble<lb/> servant—and it is supplied me<lb/> for
                considerably less than three<lb/> Dollars per annum so neither<lb/>
                <persName>Wise</persName> nor <persName>Gluck</persName> will ride in<lb/> a
                carriage from their <placeName>Montreal</placeName><lb/> income.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Are you going to complete<lb/> the Translation of my fathers<lb/>
                <persName>Reggio</persName>? Is there no Dutchman<lb/> at hand yet? My father writes
                me <persName>Mr<lb/> Gershom Kursheedt</persName> has secured<lb/> the rare copy of
                    <add>תנך</add> of which<lb/> I wrote you—and apropos<lb/> des <hi
                    rend="underline">battes</hi>
                <persName>Dr Lowe</persName> writes me<lb/> he is going to send me a copy of<lb/>
                his Circassion<add>?</add> &amp; Turkish Dictionary<lb/>—I have <add>?</add>
                <persName>David</persName>, and have<lb/> a smattering of Arabic; but I<lb/> hardly
                think am Turk enough<lb/> to give an opinion of the learned<lb/> Doctors work. It is
                gratifying</p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>to have such a man amongst us.<lb/> His work has been published at<lb/> the expense
                of the London Philological<lb/> Society. He is also going to send me<lb/> some other
                of his works published<lb/> by the London Humanistic Society<lb/> more notice should
                be taken of<lb/> him in the London Chronicle.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)"><persName>Dr Dawson</persName> the Principal<lb/> of Mc Gill
                College—a man of<lb/> great endowments and deep learning<lb/> favorably known in the
                    <placeName>United States</placeName><lb/> and <placeName>Europe</placeName> as
                one of the greatest<lb/> geologists of the day—especially<lb/> for his studies of
                the Carboniferous<lb/> Flora—is about publishing<lb/> a work called
                Archaia—wherein<lb/> he considers the alleged discrepancies<lb/> between the Mosaic
                &amp; Geological<lb/> accounts of the Cosmogony—<lb/>as well as the origin of the
                human<lb/> race. As <persName>Dr D.</persName> is celebrated as<lb/> a man of
                science, and he will</p>
            <pb n="4"/>
            <p>write in a reverent spirit, the<lb/> work is not less interesting to us<lb/> than to
                Christians. I would like<lb/> you to see it.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I require a couple of<lb/> numbers of the Occident to complete<lb/>
                my file. As <persName>Sarah Joseph</persName>—who<lb/> takes this for me—is going
                to<lb/> make some stay in your city<lb/> You can send them to me by her.<lb/> If I
                have time before the <add>?</add><lb/> I will see which are the missing<lb/> nos. I
                think I want Nos 1. &amp; 2<lb/> in vol XIV—but I will write<lb/> you again.
                Meanwhile I am Yours Truly</p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">
                <persName role="author">Abraham de Sola</persName>
            </p>
        </body>
